      <h1>Meal Prep for Weight Loss: The Complete Guide to Batch Cooking and Portion Control</h1>
      <p class="article-intro">Meal prepping is the secret weapon behind nearly every successful weight loss transformation. When your healthy meals are already cooked, portioned, and waiting in the fridge, you eliminate the decision fatigue, convenience temptations, and portion guessing that derail most diets. Research published in the International Journal of Behavioral Nutrition and Physical Activity found that people who spent more time on meal preparation ate more fruits and vegetables, consumed fewer calories from fast food, and had better overall diet quality. This guide gives you everything you need: the calorie deficit math, optimal macro ratios, batch cooking techniques, a complete 5-day meal plan at approximately 1,500 calories per day, a grocery list template, and food safety guidelines.</p>
    </header>

    <AdUnit slot="blog-top" format="horizontal" />

    <TableOfContents />

    <h2>The Calorie Deficit: Weight Loss Math Made Simple</h2>
    <p>Before you buy a single container or chop a single vegetable, you need to understand the fundamental equation of weight loss: you must consistently burn more calories than you consume. This is called a calorie deficit, and it is the non-negotiable requirement for losing body fat regardless of what diet you follow.</p>
    <p>One pound of body fat contains approximately 3,500 calories of stored energy. To lose one pound per week, you need a cumulative deficit of 3,500 calories, or about 500 calories per day. To lose 1.5 pounds per week, you need a deficit of about 750 calories per day. Deficits larger than 1,000 calories per day are generally not recommended because they lead to muscle loss, nutrient deficiencies, metabolic adaptation, and are extremely difficult to maintain.</p>

    <h3>How to Calculate Your Target Calories</h3>
    <p>The process is straightforward:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Calculate your Basal Metabolic Rate (BMR)</strong> — the number of calories your body burns at rest just to maintain basic functions like breathing, circulation, and cell repair. Use our <a href="/calorie/">calorie calculator</a> to get an accurate estimate based on your age, sex, height, and weight.</li>
      <li><strong>Multiply by an activity factor</strong> to get your Total Daily Energy Expenditure (TDEE). Sedentary (desk job, little exercise) = BMR x 1.2; Lightly active (light exercise 1-3 days/week) = BMR x 1.375; Moderately active (moderate exercise 3-5 days/week) = BMR x 1.55; Very active (hard exercise 6-7 days/week) = BMR x 1.725.</li>
      <li><strong>Subtract your deficit</strong> from your TDEE. For 1 pound per week of fat loss, subtract 500. For 1.5 pounds per week, subtract 750.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>For example, a 35-year-old woman who weighs 170 pounds, stands 5 feet 5 inches, and exercises 3 times per week might have a TDEE of approximately 2,050 calories. Subtracting 500 gives a daily target of 1,550 calories. Subtracting 750 gives a target of 1,300 calories. Most dietitians recommend that women do not go below 1,200 calories per day and men do not go below 1,500 calories per day without medical supervision.</p>

    <h2>Optimal Macro Distribution for Weight Loss</h2>
    <p>Once you know your calorie target, the next step is dividing those calories among the three macronutrients: protein, carbohydrates, and fat. While total calories determine whether you lose weight, macronutrient distribution determines what type of weight you lose (fat vs. muscle), how full you feel, and how much energy you have.</p>

    <h3>Protein: The Most Important Macro for Weight Loss</h3>
    <p>Aim for 30 to 40 percent of total calories from protein, or approximately 0.7 to 1.0 grams of protein per pound of body weight. For a 1,500-calorie diet, this means 112 to 150 grams of protein per day. Protein is crucial during weight loss for three reasons: it preserves lean muscle mass (so you lose fat, not muscle); it has the highest thermic effect of food (your body burns 20 to 30 percent of protein calories during digestion, compared to 5 to 10 percent for carbs and 0 to 3 percent for fat); and it is the most satiating macronutrient, keeping you full longer between meals. Learn more with our <a href="/macro/">macro calculator</a>.</p>

    <h3>Carbohydrates: Your Energy Source</h3>
    <p>Aim for 30 to 40 percent of total calories from carbohydrates, prioritizing complex carbs (whole grains, vegetables, legumes, fruits) over simple carbs (white bread, sugary snacks, soda). For a 1,500-calorie diet, this means 112 to 150 grams of carbs per day. Complex carbohydrates provide sustained energy, dietary fiber (which aids digestion and satiety), and essential vitamins and minerals. Do not fear carbs — they fuel your workouts and brain function. The key is choosing whole, minimally processed sources.</p>

    <h3>Fat: Essential, Not Evil</h3>
    <p>Aim for 20 to 30 percent of total calories from fat, focusing on unsaturated fats (olive oil, avocado, nuts, fatty fish) while limiting saturated and trans fats. For a 1,500-calorie diet, this means 33 to 50 grams of fat per day. Dietary fat is essential for hormone production, vitamin absorption (vitamins A, D, E, and K are fat-soluble), cell membrane integrity, and brain health. Cutting fat too low can disrupt hormone function and leave you feeling unsatisfied.</p>

    <h2>Batch Cooking Proteins: The Foundation of Meal Prep</h2>
    <p>Protein is the most time-consuming component to cook, so batch cooking your proteins on a single prep day saves the most time during the week. Here are the most efficient methods for the most popular proteins:</p>

    <h3>Chicken Breast (Baked or Grilled)</h3>
    <p>Season 3 to 4 pounds of chicken breast with salt, pepper, garlic powder, and your preferred spices. Bake at 425 degrees Fahrenheit for 20 to 25 minutes (internal temperature must reach 165 degrees Fahrenheit). Let rest for 5 minutes, then slice or dice. This yields approximately 12 to 16 servings of 4-ounce portions, each containing about 35 grams of protein and 180 calories.</p>

    <h3>Ground Turkey</h3>
    <p>Brown 2 to 3 pounds of lean (93 percent or higher) ground turkey in a large skillet over medium-high heat. Season with taco seasoning, Italian herbs, or Asian-inspired flavors (soy sauce, ginger, garlic). Drain any excess liquid. This can be used in wraps, grain bowls, stir-fries, and salads throughout the week. A 4-ounce portion contains about 22 grams of protein and 170 calories.</p>

    <h3>Hard-Boiled Eggs</h3>
    <p>Place 12 to 18 eggs in a single layer in a large pot. Cover with cold water by one inch. Bring to a rolling boil, then remove from heat, cover, and let sit for 10 to 12 minutes. Transfer to an ice bath for 5 minutes. Peel and store in the refrigerator for up to 7 days. Each large egg provides 6 grams of protein and 70 calories — perfect for snacks and salad toppings.</p>

    <h3>Salmon or White Fish</h3>
    <p>Season 2 pounds of salmon fillets with lemon, dill, salt, and pepper. Bake at 400 degrees Fahrenheit for 12 to 15 minutes. Salmon provides omega-3 fatty acids, which support heart health and reduce inflammation. A 4-ounce portion contains approximately 25 grams of protein and 230 calories.</p>

    <h2>The Portion Control Container System</h2>
    <p>One of the biggest challenges of weight loss is accurate portion sizing. Even healthy foods can derail your progress if you eat too much of them. A container-based system removes the guesswork and makes portion control nearly automatic.</p>
    <p>For a 1,500-calorie day, each meal container should hold approximately:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Protein:</strong> 4 to 6 ounces of cooked lean protein (roughly the size of your palm)</li>
      <li><strong>Complex carbs:</strong> 1/2 to 3/4 cup of cooked grains, rice, or starchy vegetables (roughly the size of your cupped hand)</li>
      <li><strong>Vegetables:</strong> 1 to 2 cups of non-starchy vegetables (fill the rest of the container)</li>
      <li><strong>Healthy fat:</strong> 1 to 2 tablespoons of olive oil, avocado, nuts, or cheese (roughly the size of your thumb)</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Invest in containers with compartments to keep foods separated. This prevents sogginess, makes reheating easier, and visually reinforces portion control. Glass containers with snap-lock lids are the gold standard — they are microwave-safe, do not absorb flavors or stains, and last for years.</p>

    <h2>5-Day Sample Meal Plan (Approximately 1,500 Calories Per Day)</h2>
    <p>This sample plan provides roughly 1,500 calories per day with approximately 150 grams of protein, 130 grams of carbohydrates, and 45 grams of fat. Adjust portions up or down based on your individual calorie target.</p>

    <h3>Day 1 (Monday)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Breakfast (400 cal):</strong> Overnight oats made with 1/2 cup rolled oats, 1 scoop protein powder, 1/2 cup unsweetened almond milk, 1/2 cup Greek yogurt, and 1/2 cup mixed berries.</li>
      <li><strong>Lunch (450 cal):</strong> Grilled chicken breast (5 oz) with 3/4 cup brown rice, 1 cup roasted broccoli, and 1 tablespoon olive oil drizzle.</li>
      <li><strong>Snack (150 cal):</strong> 2 hard-boiled eggs with a handful of cherry tomatoes.</li>
      <li><strong>Dinner (500 cal):</strong> Baked salmon (5 oz) with 1 cup roasted sweet potato cubes and 2 cups mixed green salad with 1 tablespoon balsamic vinaigrette.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Day 2 (Tuesday)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Breakfast (380 cal):</strong> 2-egg omelet with spinach, bell peppers, and 1/4 cup feta cheese. 1 slice whole wheat toast.</li>
      <li><strong>Lunch (470 cal):</strong> Turkey lettuce wraps — 5 oz seasoned ground turkey, diced tomatoes, sliced avocado (1/4), and salsa in large butter lettuce leaves. Side of 15 baby carrots.</li>
      <li><strong>Snack (130 cal):</strong> 1 medium apple with 1 tablespoon almond butter.</li>
      <li><strong>Dinner (520 cal):</strong> Chicken stir-fry — 5 oz chicken breast with 2 cups mixed vegetables (bell peppers, snap peas, mushrooms, broccoli) in 1 tablespoon sesame oil and low-sodium soy sauce. Served over 1/2 cup jasmine rice.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Day 3 (Wednesday)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Breakfast (410 cal):</strong> Smoothie — 1 scoop protein powder, 1 cup frozen mixed berries, 1/2 banana, 1 cup unsweetened almond milk, 1 tablespoon peanut butter.</li>
      <li><strong>Lunch (440 cal):</strong> Large salad — 2 cups mixed greens, 5 oz grilled chicken, 1/4 cup chickpeas, cherry tomatoes, cucumber, 1/4 avocado, 2 tablespoons light vinaigrette.</li>
      <li><strong>Snack (120 cal):</strong> 3/4 cup low-fat cottage cheese with cinnamon.</li>
      <li><strong>Dinner (530 cal):</strong> Lean beef (5 oz) with 1 cup quinoa, 1 cup steamed asparagus, and 1 tablespoon olive oil.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Day 4 (Thursday)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Breakfast (390 cal):</strong> Greek yogurt parfait — 1 cup non-fat Greek yogurt, 1/3 cup granola, 1/2 cup sliced strawberries, 1 tablespoon honey.</li>
      <li><strong>Lunch (460 cal):</strong> Whole wheat turkey wrap — 4 oz deli turkey, 1 slice Swiss cheese, lettuce, tomato, mustard in a whole wheat tortilla. Side of 1 cup raw bell pepper strips.</li>
      <li><strong>Snack (140 cal):</strong> 1/4 cup mixed nuts (almonds, walnuts, cashews).</li>
      <li><strong>Dinner (510 cal):</strong> Baked cod (6 oz) with lemon-herb seasoning, 1 cup roasted Brussels sprouts, and 3/4 cup mashed sweet potato.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Day 5 (Friday)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Breakfast (400 cal):</strong> 2 whole wheat pancakes (4-inch) with 1 tablespoon pure maple syrup, 2 turkey sausage links, and 1/2 cup blueberries.</li>
      <li><strong>Lunch (450 cal):</strong> Chicken and black bean bowl — 5 oz shredded chicken, 1/2 cup black beans, 1/2 cup brown rice, 2 tablespoons salsa, 2 tablespoons plain Greek yogurt (as sour cream substitute), and shredded lettuce.</li>
      <li><strong>Snack (130 cal):</strong> 1 string cheese and 1 medium pear.</li>
      <li><strong>Dinner (520 cal):</strong> Turkey meatballs (5 oz) with 1 cup whole wheat pasta, 1/2 cup marinara sauce, and 2 cups side salad with 1 tablespoon Italian dressing.</li>
    </ul>

