    <h2>Food Safety and Storage Times</h2>
    <p>Food safety is critical when meal prepping. Improperly stored food can harbor bacteria that cause foodborne illness, so follow these guidelines carefully.</p>

    <h3>Refrigerator Storage (40 degrees Fahrenheit or below)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Cooked chicken, turkey, beef, pork:</strong> 3 to 4 days</li>
      <li><strong>Cooked fish and seafood:</strong> 2 to 3 days</li>
      <li><strong>Cooked rice, pasta, quinoa:</strong> 3 to 5 days</li>
      <li><strong>Cooked vegetables:</strong> 3 to 7 days (softer vegetables deteriorate faster)</li>
      <li><strong>Hard-boiled eggs (peeled):</strong> up to 7 days</li>
      <li><strong>Cut fruit:</strong> 3 to 5 days</li>
      <li><strong>Dressings and sauces (store separately):</strong> check label expiration</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Freezer Storage (0 degrees Fahrenheit or below)</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Cooked meats:</strong> 2 to 3 months for best quality</li>
      <li><strong>Cooked rice and grains:</strong> up to 6 months</li>
      <li><strong>Soups and stews:</strong> 2 to 3 months</li>
      <li><strong>Cooked vegetables:</strong> 1 to 2 months (texture may change)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Key Food Safety Rules</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Cool hot food to room temperature within 1 hour before refrigerating (do not leave food at room temperature for more than 2 hours total).</li>
      <li>Divide large batches into shallow containers for faster cooling.</li>
      <li>Label every container with the date it was prepared.</li>
      <li>Store raw and cooked foods separately to prevent cross-contamination.</li>
      <li>Reheat leftovers to an internal temperature of 165 degrees Fahrenheit before eating.</li>
      <li>When in doubt, throw it out. If food looks, smells, or tastes off, do not risk it.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Meal Prep Tips for Long-Term Success</h2>
    <p>The biggest challenge with meal prepping is not the first week — it is week 8. Here are strategies to make meal prep a sustainable habit rather than a temporary effort:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Start small.</strong> If you have never meal prepped before, start by prepping just lunches for the workweek. Once that feels automatic, add breakfasts, then snacks, then dinners.</li>
      <li><strong>Rotate recipes every 2 weeks.</strong> Eating the same five meals for months will lead to burnout. Keep a rotation of 10 to 15 recipes and swap them regularly.</li>
      <li><strong>Prep components, not just full meals.</strong> Sometimes it is more flexible to batch cook individual components (proteins, grains, roasted vegetables) and assemble different combinations throughout the week.</li>
      <li><strong>Use theme nights.</strong> Assign themes to each day (Taco Tuesday, Stir-Fry Wednesday, Mediterranean Thursday) to simplify planning while maintaining variety.</li>
      <li><strong>Invest in quality tools.</strong> A good knife, large cutting board, sheet pans, a rice cooker, and quality containers make prep day faster and more enjoyable.</li>
      <li><strong>Prep on the same day each week.</strong> Consistency builds habit. Most people prep on Sunday afternoons, but choose whatever day works best for your schedule.</li>
      <li><strong>Track your progress.</strong> Use our <a href="/calorie/">calorie calculator</a> and <a href="/macro/">macro calculator</a> to monitor your intake and adjust as you lose weight. Your calorie needs decrease as your weight decreases, so recalculate every 10 to 15 pounds lost.</li>
    </ul>

